{"questionId":"27948","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Elsie, a librarian, wants to investigate the length of time, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math> minutes, that people spent in her library on a particular day.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Elsie’s data for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>160</mn></math> people who visited the library on that particular day is shown in the following table.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/a22ae009c52eae231f00243099926ab50be0a3cb.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Elsie assumes her data to be representative of future visitors to the library.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following box and whisker diagram shows the times, in minutes, that the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>160</mn></math> visitors&nbsp;spent in the library.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/04e5f0edc42f9c53d1005baa871d5081ee3d96e5.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the interquartile range.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award<em><strong> M1</strong></em> for both correct quartiles seen.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>34</mn></math>&nbsp; minutes&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27948","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.1h","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the interquartile range.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"h","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.2—Histograms, CF graphs, box plots"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}